# 🚨 Major Validator Update v2.0 🚨
- 🛡️ Time gated scoring
- 🛠️ Preparation for Bittensor version 8.5 support

## Validators Please Update
- This version includes significant changes to the scoring mechanic, failing to update ASAP may result in loss of vTrust

## Time Gated Scoring
- We only consider predictions within the last 21 days when setting weights
- We prioritize predictions from the last 5 days (they are weighted higher, and weighted equally), with weight-per-score dropping off linearly from 6 days ago until 21 days ago
- No penalty for not being reg'd for the entire 21-day time window
- We now send the true "weighted" scores to the web server (these scores reflect the scaling performed in case of low scored prediction volumes or market targeting), so the website Rankings Page `score` column should better reflect incentive

"We now send the true "weighted" scores to the web server (these scores reflect the scaling performed in case of low scored prediction volumes or market targeting), so the website Rankings Page score column should better reflect incentive"

I calculate my cumulative scores (including penalties) for predictions myself and they are much higher than those displayed on the site. Does this mean that seeing a low score on the site means that the problem is in the incorrect assessment/weight by one of the validators?

No. You can’t actually calculate your own penalties without having access to every validator’s database because penalties are associated with data those validators are storing, and you can’t be sure which validators end up scoring which of your predictions with certainty.

So I keep records of each of my predictions from the moment the miner starts, and then compare them with the sales facts. So yes, I know my score well for each of the validators. Of course, I don’t take into account the weights of the validators, but this part of the algorithm cannot drop the score by 10% for the top miner.
That's why I asked, what should a low score on a website of a top miner mean to me?
You may be tracking your own data, but that data is not *necessarily* reflective of what validators are storing - that's an important distinction to make.

As for your original question, the validators are all running the same code, but not necessarily working with the same data. So each validator's "assessment" is correct per the data they're working with. A low score for a top miner is usually more indicative of other scores being high relative to incentive, not that miner's score being low relative to incentive.

From a game theory perspective, the best time to swap קalpha for TAO is when registration costs peak each week

We’ll see the full impact of our weekly registration cycle in the coming weeks, but the effects are already visible today. This system favors healthy subnets with low operating costs. Compared to compute-heavy subnets where miners face high daily GPU costs, this model benefits prediction subnets like ours. Ultimately, subnets with strong products and high competition will achieve the healthiest emissions

Hey everyone, I wanted to post this update about sorting out what's going on with miner incentive. There has been 1 validator update since dTao launched, and 1 web server fix. I'll talk about each in turn.

## Validator Update on Monday
This change (https://github.com/Nickel5-Inc/Nextplace/commit/f5b87e38587fb7f687ab96fb753625f4589d9ed1) was focused around identifying miners in the metagraph. Previous to dTao we used stake. That doesn't work well with dTao so now we use dividends. This change was thoroughly tested and I'm confident that it works. Other small changes involved adding some type declarations and incrementing the version number.

## Web Server Update on Thursday
We all spoke at length about this feature when it came out. Due to the volume of data moving through this subnet and the design of bittensor networking, we had to allow a validator with 0 scores for a miner to check if other validators have scores for that same miner. This allows miners to get incentive much faster. The API we were using to do this had expired, and we updated it. That is all.

I don't think that either of these updates have anything to do with the sudden change in OTF's validator weights (though the timing is suspicious), largely because

3) Neither of the above changes can really explain the sudden change in OTF's incentive distribution

Looking at the screenshots shared above, it's pretty clear that something is wrong with OTF's validator. They suddenly and dramatically changed all weights they were setting.
